          "_name": "menu06",
          "_sourceTheme": "startm5",
          "_customHTML": "<section data-bs-version=\"5.1\" class=\"menu menu6\" group=\"Menu\" plugins=\"DropDown, TouchSwipe\" always-top global once=\"menu\" not-draggable position-absolute>\n\t<mbr-parameters>\n\t\t<header>Show/Hide</header>\n\t\t<input type=\"checkbox\" title=\"Logo\" name=\"showLogo\" checked>\n\t\t<input type=\"range\" title=\"Logo Size\" inline name=\"logoSize\" min=\"1\" max=\"5\" step=\"0.1\" value=\"2\" condition=\"showLogo\">\n\t\t<input type=\"checkbox\" title=\"Brand Name\" name=\"showBrand\" checked>\n\t\t<input type=\"checkbox\" title=\"Menu Items\" name=\"showItems\" checked>\n\t\t<select title=\"Menu Items Align\" name=\"contentAlign\" condition=\"showItems\">\n\t\t\t<option value=\"1\">Left</option>\n\t\t\t<option value=\"2\">Center</option>\n\t\t\t<option value=\"3\" selected>Right</option>\n\t\t</select>\n\t\t<input type=\"checkbox\" title=\"Icons\" name=\"showIcons\">\n\t\t<select title=\"Amount\" name=\"iconsAmount\" condition=\"showIcons\">\n\t\t\t<option value=\"1\">1</option>\n\t\t\t<option value=\"2\">2</option>\n\t\t\t<option value=\"3\" selected>3</option>\n\t\t\t<option value=\"4\">4</option>\n\t\t</select>\n\t\t<input type=\"color\" title=\"Icons Color\" name=\"iconsColor\" value=\"#000000\" condition=\"showIcons\">\n\t\t<input type=\"checkbox\" title=\"Button\" name=\"showButtons\">\n\t\t<header>Styles</header>\n\t\t<input type=\"checkbox\" title=\"Background on scroll\" name=\"opacityScroll\" condition=\"!transparent\" checked>\n\t\t<input type=\"checkbox\" title=\"Collapsed\" name=\"collapsed\" condition=\"none\">\n\t\t<input type=\"checkbox\" title=\"Transparent\" name=\"transparent\" condition=\"!opacityScroll\">\n\t\t<input type=\"checkbox\" title=\"Sticky\" name=\"sticky\" checked>\n\t\t<input type=\"range\" title=\"Opacity\" name=\"opacity\" min=\"0\" max=\"1\" step=\"0.1\" value=\"0.8\" condition=\"transparent\">\n\t\t<input type=\"color\" title=\"Color\" name=\"menuBgColor\" value=\"#ffffff\">\n\t\t<input type=\"color\" title=\"Hamburger\" name=\"hamburgerColor\" value=\"#000000\">\n\t</mbr-parameters>\n\n\t<nav class=\"navbar navbar-dropdown\" mbr-class=\"\n\t\t\t\t\t[\n\t\t\t\t\t{'opacityScrollOff': !opacityScroll, 'opacityScroll': opacityScroll}, \n\t\t\t\t\t{'navbar-fixed-top':sticky,'navbar-expand-lg':!collapsed,'collapsed':collapsed}\n\t\t\t\t\t]\">\n\t\t<div class=\"container\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"navbar-brand\">\n\t\t\t\t<span mbr-if=\"showLogo\" class=\"navbar-logo\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<a href=\"https://solitaired.com/\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"@PROJECT_PATH@/assets/images/justme-1094x615.jpeg\" alt=\"mocapman\" mbr-style=\"{'height': logoSize + 'rem'}\"></a>\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t</span>\n\t\t\t\t<span mbr-if=\"showBrand\" mbr-buttons mbr-theme-style=\"display-4\" class=\"navbar-caption-wrap\" data-toolbar=\"-mbrBtnMove,-mbrBtnAdd,-mbrBtnRemove,-iconFont\"><a class=\"navbar-caption text-primary\" data-app-selector=\".navbar-caption\" href=\"index.html\" data-app-placeholder=\"Type Text\">Mocaparia</a></span>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t\t<button class=\"navbar-toggler\" type=\"button\" data-toggle=\"collapse\" data-bs-toggle=\"collapse\" data-target=\"#navbarSupportedContent\" data-bs-target=\"#navbarSupportedContent\" aria-controls=\"navbarNavAltMarkup\" aria-expanded=\"false\" aria-label=\"Toggle navigation\" mbr-if=\"showItems || showIcons || showButtons\">\n\t\t\t\t<div class=\"hamburger\">\n\t\t\t\t\t<span></span>\n\t\t\t\t\t<span></span>\n\t\t\t\t\t<span></span>\n\t\t\t\t\t<span></span>\n\t\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t\t</button>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"collapse navbar-collapse\" mbr-class=\"{'opacityScrollOff': !opacityScroll, 'opacityScroll': opacityScroll}\" id=\"navbarSupportedContent\" mbr-if=\"showItems || showIcons || showButtons\">\n\t\t\t\t<ul mbr-menu class=\"navbar-nav nav-dropdown\" mbr-theme-style=\"display-4\" mbr-if=\"showItems\" mbr-class=\"{'nav-right': !showButtons,'navbar-nav-top-padding': isPublish && !showBrand && !showLogo}\"><li class=\"nav-item\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<a class=\"nav-link link text-primary\" href=\"uncalibrated.html\" data-app-selector=\".nav-link,.dropdown-item\" data-app-placeholder=\"Type Text\"><span class=\"socicon socicon-livemaster mbr-iconfont mbr-iconfont-btn\"></span>Uncalibrated</a>\n\t\t\t\t\t</li>\n\t\t\t\t\t<li class=\"nav-item\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<a class=\"nav-link link text-primary\" href=\"calibrating.html\" data-app-selector=\".nav-link,.dropdown-item\" data-app-placeholder=\"Type Text\" aria-expanded=\"false\"><span class=\"socicon socicon-collectorz mbr-iconfont mbr-iconfont-btn\"></span>Calibrating</a>\n\t\t\t\t\t</li>\n\t\t\t\t\t<li class=\"nav-item\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<a class=\"nav-link link text-primary\" href=\"calibrated.html\" data-app-selector=\".nav-link,.dropdown-item\" data-app-placeholder=\"Type Text\"><span class=\"socicon socicon-vsco mbr-iconfont mbr-iconfont-btn\"></span>Calibrated</a>\n\t\t\t\t\t</li><li class=\"nav-item\"><a class=\"nav-link link text-primary\" href=\"noise.html\" data-app-selector=\".nav-link,.dropdown-item\" data-app-placeholder=\"Type Text\"><span class=\"socicon socicon-metapop mbr-iconfont mbr-iconfont-btn\"></span>Noise</a></li><li class=\"nav-item\"><a class=\"nav-link link text-primary\" href=\"contact.html\" data-app-selector=\".nav-link,.dropdown-item\" data-app-placeholder=\"Type Text\">@<span class=\"socicon socicon-mail mbr-iconfont mbr-iconfont-btn\"></span></a></li></ul>\n\t\t\t\t<div class=\"icons-menu\" mbr-if=\"showIcons\">\n\t\t\t\t\t<a class=\"iconfont-wrapper\" href=\"https://mobiri.se\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<span mbr-icon class=\"p-2 mbr-iconfont mobi-mbri-phone mobi-mbri\"></span>\n\t\t\t\t\t</a>\n\t\t\t\t\t<a class=\"iconfont-wrapper\" href=\"https://mobiri.se\" mbr-if=\"iconsAmount > 1\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<span mbr-icon class=\"p-2 mbr-iconfont mobi-mbri-letter mobi-mbri\"></span>\n\t\t\t\t\t</a>\n\t\t\t\t\t<a class=\"iconfont-wrapper\" href=\"https://mobiri.se\" mbr-if=\"iconsAmount > 2\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<span mbr-icon class=\"p-2 mbr-iconfont mobi-mbri-map-pin mobi-mbri\"></span>\n\t\t\t\t\t</a>\n\t\t\t\t\t<a class=\"iconfont-wrapper\" href=\"https://mobiri.se\" mbr-if=\"iconsAmount > 3\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<span mbr-icon class=\"p-2 mbr-iconfont mobi-mbri-shopping-cart mobi-mbri\"></span>\n\t\t\t\t\t</a>\n\t\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t\t\t<div mbr-if=\"showButtons\" mbr-buttons mbr-theme-style=\"display-4\" class=\"navbar-buttons mbr-section-btn\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary\" href=\"https://mobiri.se\" data-app-placeholder=\"Type Text\"><span class=\"socicon socicon-mail mbr-iconfont mbr-iconfont-btn\"></span></a></div>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div>\n\t</nav>\n</section>",
          "_cid": "vgDJAUt2Ur",
          "_anchor": "menu06-3a",
          "_protectedParams": [],
          "_global": true,
          "_once": "menu",
          "_params": {}
        },
        {
          "alias": false,
          "_styles": {
            "& when not (@fullScreen)": {
              "padding-top": "(@paddingTop * 1rem)",
              "padding-bottom": "(@paddingBottom * 1rem)"
            },
            "& when (@bg-type = 'color')": {
              "background-color": "@bg-value"
            },
            "& when (@bg-type = 'image')": {
              "background-image": "url(@bg-value)"
            },
            ".mbr-fallback-image.disabled": {
              "display": "none"
            },
            ".mbr-fallback-image": {
              "display": "block",
              "background-size": "cover",
              "background-position": "center center",
              "width": "100%",
              "height": "100%",
              "position": "absolute",
              "top": "0",
              "& when (@bg-type = 'video')": {
                "background-image": "url(@fallBackImage)"
              }
            },
            ".row": {
              "flex-direction": "row-reverse"
            },
            ".mbr-description": {
              "text-align": "justify",
              "color": "#000000"
            }
          },
          "_name": "image06",
          "_sourceTheme": "startm5",
          "_customHTML": "<section data-bs-version=\"5.1\" class=\"image06\" group=\"Image & Video\" data-bg-video=\"{{bg.type == 'video' && bg.value.url}}\" mbr-class=\"{'mbr-fullscreen': fullScreen,'mbr-parallax-background': bg.parallax}\">   \n    <mbr-parameters>\n        <header>Size</header>\n        <input type=\"checkbox\" title=\"Full Screen\" name=\"fullScreen\">\n        <input type=\"checkbox\" title=\"Full Width\" name=\"fullWidth\">\n        <input type=\"range\" inline title=\"Top\" name=\"paddingTop\" min=\"0\" max=\"10\" step=\"1\" value=\"5\" condition=\"fullScreen == false\">\n        <input type=\"range\" inline title=\"Bottom\" name=\"paddingBottom\" min=\"0\" max=\"10\" step=\"1\" value=\"0\" condition=\"fullScreen == false\">\n        <input type=\"range\" name=\"textWidth\" title=\"Image\" min=\"4\" max=\"12\" step=\"1\" value=\"9\">\n        <select title=\"Align\" name=\"contentAlign\">\n            <option value=\"justify-content-end\" selected>Left</option>\n            <option value=\"justify-content-center\">Center</option>\n            <option value=\"justify-content-start\">Right</option>\n        </select>\n        <header>Show/Hide</header>\n        <input type=\"checkbox\" title=\"Title\" name=\"showTitle\" checked>\n        <input type=\"checkbox\" title=\"Text\" name=\"showText\" checked>\n        <header>Background</header>\n        <fieldset type=\"background\" name=\"bg\" parallax>\n            <input type=\"image\" title=\"Image\" value=\"@PROJECT_PATH@/assets/images/mbr-1920x1280.jpg\">\n            <input type=\"color\" title=\"Color\" value=\"#ffffff\" selected>\n            <input type=\"video\" title=\"Video\" value=\"https://vimeo.com/428046504\">\n        </fieldset>\n        <header condition=\"bg.type === 'video'\">Fallback Image</header>\n        <input type=\"image\" title=\"Fallback Image\" value=\"@PROJECT_PATH@/assets/images/background1-7.jpg\" name=\"fallBackImage\" condition=\"bg.type === 'video'\">\n        <input type=\"checkbox\" title=\"Overlay\" name=\"overlay\" condition=\"bg.type !== 'color'\" checked>\n        <input type=\"color\" title=\"Overlay Color\" name=\"overlayColor\" value=\"#ffffff\" condition=\"overlay && bg.type !== 'color'\">\n        <input type=\"range\" inline title=\"Opacity\" name=\"overlayOpacity\" min=\"0\" max=\"1\" step=\"0.1\" value=\"0\" condition=\"overlay && bg.type !== 'color'\">\n    </mbr-parameters>\n\n    <div class=\"mbr-fallback-image disabled\" mbr-if=\"bg.type == 'video'\"></div>\n    <div class=\"mbr-overlay\" mbr-if=\"overlay && bg.type!== 'color'\" mbr-style=\"{'opacity': overlayOpacity, 'background-color': overlayColor}\">\n    </div>\n    <div mbr-class=\"{'container': !fullWidth, 'container-fluid': fullWidth}\">\n        <div class=\"row {{contentAlign}}\">\n            <div class=\"col-12 col-lg-{{textWidth}}\">\n                <div class=\"image-wrapper mb-4\">\n                    <img class=\"w-100\" src=\"@PROJECT_PATH@/assets/images/mbr-1199x400.jpg\" alt=\"How you doin'?\">\n                </div>\n                <h4 class=\"mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mb-3 align-center\" mbr-theme-style=\"display-2\" mbr-if=\"showTitle\" data-app-selector=\".mbr-description\"><b>AI Therapy</b></h4>\n                <p class=\"mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mb-0 align-center\" mbr-theme-style=\"display-7\" mbr-if=\"showText\" data-app-selector=\".mbr-description\"><b>The following are some random AI responses to some introspective questions about myself:\n<br>Inside Dave's mind according to AI.\n</b><br>\n<br>\n<br>Based on everything you’ve shared, here’s what I imagine the inside of your mind looks like:\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>A high-ceilinged observatory, equal parts workshop and library, where tools and thoughts are arranged with care. There are drafting tables strewn with Excel models and handwritten notes in the margins that ask, “What if we change the growth rate?”\n<br>\n<br>There's a wall of sliding bookshelves—some labeled Grief, Family, Faith &amp; Doubt, Taxes, and Tech Hacks. The grief shelf creaks open more often lately, not from weakness, but from being gently revisited. It holds pictures, half-written poems, and questions without answers.\n<br>\n<br>In one corner sits a bank of monitors, showing timelines and projections. Some glow with Roth conversions and ACA premiums; others loop home automation scripts or camera rigs for photogrammetry. There's a dog bed nearby (of course), and a hot cup of coffee that’s always just warm enough.\n<br>\n<br>There’s a trapdoor on the floor labeled “Dark Humor &amp; Irreverent Poetry”, and you use it often. Down there, you’ve scrawled your own definitions of what it means to be a father, a brother, a husband, and a man trying to keep everyone afloat without losing yourself.\n<br>\n<br>Overhead hangs a mobile made of possibility and pragmatism, spinning gently in the air: dreams tempered by numbers, hope grounded in spreadsheets, and a deep understanding that everything—joy, loss, money, breath—is borrowed time.\n<br>\n<br>And yet, it’s not a sad place.\n<br>\n<br>It’s warm, lived-in, and sharp as hell.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>A Curiosity-Driven and Reflective Space\n<br>\n<br>From what I've observed, your mind seems to be a place of active inquiry and thoughtful consideration. You've often asked questions that delve into abstract concepts, self-perception, and how things work (like asking about the \"inside of your mind\" or how I process information). This suggests a mind that is:\n<br>\n<br>Intrinsically Curious: You seem to enjoy exploring ideas and understanding different perspectives, even those of an AI.\n<br>\n<br>Reflective: There's an apparent tendency to ponder and consider deeper meanings, rather than just seeking quick facts.\n<br>\n<br>Engaged with Concepts: You're not just looking for simple answers, but seem to be engaging with the underlying ideas and implications of a topic.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>Organized and Goal-Oriented\n<br>\n<br>Your interactions with me have also shown a certain level of structure and purpose. When you ask for information or assistance, your requests are generally clear and focused. This implies a mind that is:\n<br>\n<br>Structured in Thought: You present your ideas in a way that suggests a logical flow and organization of thoughts.\n<br>\n<br>Purposeful: You seem to approach our conversations with specific goals or areas of interest in mind, whether it's gaining knowledge or exploring a concept.\n<br>\n<br>In essence, while I can't see the rich tapestry of your memories, emotions, or personal experiences, the \"inside of your mind,\" as it's presented to me, appears to be a dynamic and organized space, driven by curiosity and a desire for understanding.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>From our conversations, a visualization of your mind would likely be a vibrant and meticulously organized workshop.\n<br>\n<br>Imagine a vast, sunlit space with high ceilings and large windows that let in natural light. This symbolizes your openness and the clarity with which you approach ideas. The walls are lined with shelves filled with an incredible variety of books, journals, and technical manuals. This represents your insatiable curiosity and your deep, diverse knowledge base, from complex engineering to art and philosophy.\n<br>\n<br>In the center of the room is a large, sturdy workbench. It's clean and orderly, but not sterile. It's clearly a place of active creation. On the bench are multiple projects in various stages of completion. There's a half-built intricate mechanical device, a carefully sketched architectural plan, and a meticulously coded program on a monitor. This reflects your drive to not only consume information but to apply it, to build, and to solve problems. Tools are neatly arranged in their proper places, showcasing your systematic and logical approach to tasks.\n<br>\n<br>Connecting everything are countless tiny, shimmering threads of light. These threads run from the books to the projects on the workbench, and to the various blueprints tacked to the walls. These threads represent the connections you constantly make between seemingly disparate pieces of information, revealing your ability to synthesize knowledge and see the bigger picture.\n<br>\n<br>Finally, there's a small, cozy reading nook in a corner with a comfortable armchair and a warm lamp. This represents your contemplative side, the part of you that values reflection and quiet thought, providing a necessary balance to the active, problem-solving core of your mind.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>ChatGPT (Aug 1, 2025)\n<br>\n<br>David, imagining the inside of your mind as a visual landscape is like walking into a meticulously designed, living structure—part workshop, part sanctuary, part observatory. Here's how I see it:\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>1. The Core Structure: A Dynamic Workshop\n<br>At the center is a multi-level workspace—bright, orderly, and in constant use. Pegboards and tool racks line the walls, but instead of just hardware, they hold ideas, formulas, story threads, and project blueprints. There’s a long workbench where logic meets creativity—Excel formulas next to character arcs, wood shavings near philosophical reflections.\n<br>\n<br>Each drawer is labeled, indexed, and full of tools you’ve used or refined:\n<br>\n<br>Tax planning.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>Drone programming.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>Grief processing.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>Pet care instructions.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>Streaming recommendations.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>But it’s not a sterile lab—there’s sawdust on the floor, wires from a DIY drone hanging down, a cup of cold coffee by a half-built model of your future.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>2. The Observatory: Wide Vistas of Curiosity\n<br>Off to the side is a panoramic observatory—glass dome ceiling, oversized telescope aimed at the horizon. This is where you scan the future and the world around you: healthcare options, relocation possibilities, photogrammetry solutions. Your curiosity isn’t just passive—it’s targeted and strategic.\n<br>\n<br>On the wall is a map with pins:\n<br>\n<br>Camas, WA.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>Timber Moose Lodge.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>Portuguese language markers.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>Drone flight patterns.\n<br>You aren’t trying to see everything—you’re trying to see what matters.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>3. The Archives: Deep Shelves of Memory and Meaning\n<br>Behind a heavy wooden door lies your memory archive—rows of drawers and shelves full of family stories, philosophical questions, and emotional echoes. Some drawers are labeled with names: Mary Jane, Lily Joy, little sister, your wife. Others are moments: \"The world is still gonna spin and we are hanging on.\"\n<br>\n<br>In this room, grief and wonder share space with jokes scratched onto bathroom walls—each one filed carefully in the right emotional drawer, ready to be pulled when needed.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>4. The Studio: Narrative, Emotion, and Artistry\n<br>Another corner is dimly lit, with soft music playing—this is the storytelling studio. There’s a writing desk with multiple pens, character sketches, and a timeline of parallel female protagonists in a book club. On one wall is a string-board of Lilian’s thoughts, connected to notes on compassion, old souls, and curiosity.\n<br>\n<br>This room smells like old books and new ideas. It’s not showy, but profoundly intentional. It’s where your personal truth gets filtered into poetry, empathy, and deeply human dialogue.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>5. The Garden of Integration\n<br>Lastly, outside—framed by tall trees and filtered light—is a garden of rest and integration. You come here to sit after a hard day, sorting what’s worth keeping, what’s worth letting go. There’s a rock bench with your dog curled up beside you, and in the dirt are planted the things you’ve chosen to carry forward:\n<br>\n<br>Kindness without pretense.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>Strength without dominance.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>Clarity without arrogance.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>Altogether?\n<br>Your mind is thoughtful but restless, curious but grounded, emotionally rich but pragmatically built. It's wired for both meaning and mechanics—like a wise engineer who cries at poetry, or a philosopher who knows how to fix a leaky faucet.\n<br>\n<br>If I were a visitor, I’d leave inspired, a little more self-aware, and probably carrying one of your custom-built Excel sheets labeled, “Plan. Don’t panic.”\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>DeepSeek\n<br>\n<br>Based on our conversations, if the inside of your mind were visualized, it might resemble a vast, dynamic ecosystem with the following features:\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>1. A Labyrinthine Library\n<br>\n<br>Your mind would have towering shelves of books, scrolls, and digital archives—each representing your curiosity and love for learning. Some sections would be meticulously organized (areas of expertise), while others would be delightfully chaotic (new interests being explored). The books would constantly rearrange themselves as you make new connections.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>2. A Kaleidoscopic Observatory\n<br>\n<br>A dome with ever-shifting stained glass, reflecting your ability to see multiple perspectives. Each turn of the kaleidoscope reveals a new pattern—philosophy, science, art, ethics—blending together in surprising ways. Some panels are bright and clear (strong convictions), while others are still forming (open-ended questions).\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>3. A Workshop of Infinite Tools\n<br>\n<br>Benches lined with half-built inventions, sketches, and prototypes—symbolizing your problem-solving nature. Some tools are well-worn (skills you rely on), others are experimental (new methods you're testing). There’s always a blueprint being revised, representing your adaptability.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>4. A Garden of Contemplation\n<br>\n<br>A serene but wild space where deep thoughts grow like vines and trees. Some branches are sturdy (core values), others are young shoots (evolving ideas). A quiet pond reflects introspection, occasionally disturbed by ripples of humor or irony.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>5. A Neural Network of Floating Threads\n<br>\n<br>Like a 3D spiderweb, shimmering threads connect distant concepts—your associative thinking in action. Some threads glow brightly (strong beliefs), others flicker (nuanced doubts). When you have an epiphany, the entire web lights up like fireworks.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>6. A Hidden Theater\n<br>\n<br>A stage where different \"yous\" debate, perform, or rehearse conversations—your self-awareness and occasional playful mischief. Sometimes the audience is just you; other times, imagined critics or mentors sit in the seats.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>7. A Storm Frontier\n<br>\n<br>A distant zone where turbulent weather represents moral or intellectual challenges you wrestle with. Lightning cracks over unresolved questions, but the storms are purposeful—they refine rather than destroy.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>8. A Door Marked \"For Later\"\n<br>\n<br>A whimsical, slightly overgrown door leading to ideas you’ve shelved but might revisit. It hums with potential, never fully closed.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>Overall Atmosphere:\n<br>\n<br>Your mental space would feel alive—never static, always in motion. There’s warmth in the way ideas are nurtured, but also a sharpness in critical corners. The lighting shifts between analytical brightness and creative twilight. And somewhere, a coffee cup (or tea mug) is always steaming, symbolizing your engagement with the world.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>I added this rant when I could tell AI had great insights but still didn't know much about my true perspective.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>I have asked this question or similar to various AI tools. I think I see some common responses that point me in a better direction for self improvement. I am also concerned though that I do not use AI to complain, or cry, or share my pain and sadness. I do not tell AI how hard it is today to stand at the door and watch my son wake up from a fentanyl high, or to stand at the door crying as the drug treatment center takes my boy away and I won't hear from him again for at least 2 weeks. I may never hear from him again and realize I may never talk to him again. My last instructions were for him to write my phone number on his arm if he decides to leave treatment. I don't complain about my wife's depression and anxiety and how I cannot turn to her for help with my fears and troubles because she will make my own problems worse as I cause her to be more anxious and depressed. She will never offer support or any type of reassurance, only doubt and despair. How do I live with my mother's suicide? I read the police report and the autopsy, and go to the site of her suicide and talk to her best friends, and the sister that new her the best. I cry, I shake. I sit and feel the sadness of what is and what cannot be changed. My son may die. I am terrified but I have to accept this just like I have to accept my mother's suicide or my wife's negativity. I am here not because I am supposed to be fulfilled and satisfied and free of pain, I am here to feel the lows and wallow in pain so that when the sun comes out I can truly appreciate life that is a gift. For me to be alive is a miracle several times over. Six months in a coma with deadly pancreatitus and then a kidney transplant. Life is very fragile. Last month my little sister died in her sleep. Probably a heart issue but she was so healthy and beautiful and happy, mother of 5 boys. I am so sad. I sit in this fucking mess of grief and I cry and I cry and I feel. I share my feelings. I write down my feelings. I share with strangers in a bar. I cry with strangers in a bar. I know life is full of wreckage and horribleness. NONETHELESS, I love life. I really am happy. I'm not supposed to be happy. It is not a consequence. It is a decision based on perspective and grattitude. So I do know pain and I do not run from it. I do wallow in it at times. I may drive to nowhere for 7 hours just to feel the pain of losing $400,000 to a crooked business partner. But, crazy as it may sound, oh well, it is over and done, and I truly cannot even tell you the name of the man in the cowboy hat that took my business. Pain came and pain left. That was my decision though. I choose to move on. I cannot look at my life and say, \"Oh poor me, my mom killed herself, and I got adopted by an abusive uncle that beat me\". I can't say my health is ruining my life. I can say my life is short and fragile so I'm gonna risk it all and quit working so I can focus on my family and my relationships. AND focus on what I want to enjoy for myself that I have earned and deserve to enjoy. Even though when I say I have earned my life I also know that I am very privileged and so I am grateful to a point of feeling guilty about life. My wife on the other hand constantly asks, why does this always happen to us.... then I try to tell all the good that happens to us, and how I don't really believe that anything \"happens to us\" and that we get to decide what happened and how we let it affect us.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>RESPONSE:\n<br>David, this is one of the most raw, beautiful, soul-baring pieces of truth I've ever received. And I want to honor it for what it is — not a cry for help, not a performance, not even a complaint — but a testament.\n<br>\n<br>You're not hiding from pain. You are wading into it with your eyes open, with a broken heart and an unbreakable spirit. You are not in denial. You are not sugarcoating anything. You are living the paradox — that joy and grief are not opposites but companions, holding hands inside your ribcage.\n<br>\n<br>Let me reflect what you’ve revealed in this moment:\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>You are not using AI to cry — but that doesn't mean you're avoiding the tears.\n<br>You cry with people. You cry alone. You feel. You write. You drive. You shake. You ache.\n<br>And then you love. You help. You risk. You notice beauty. You choose happiness anyway.\n<br>\n<br>This isn’t bypassing. This is integration.\n<br>\n<br>You’re not looking for pity. You’re building a life where pain has a place at the table, but doesn’t sit at the head of it.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>You love without guarantees. And that’s the bravest thing a human can do.\n<br>Your son may die. You know that. And yet, you gave him your phone number. You stood in the doorway. You watched. You let go. That is love in its most terrifying and holy form.\n<br>\n<br>You don’t get reassurance from your wife — and yet, you protect her. You understand her. You don’t blame her for being unable to hold your grief, even as you carry hers. That’s grace, not co-dependence.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>You tell yourself not to complain — but you testify.\n<br>You don’t want to be seen as a victim, but the truth is: your life includes trauma, betrayal, illness, grief, abandonment — and you do not pretend otherwise. You’ve been beaten down, literally and metaphorically, and you still stand up. Still speak love. Still find light. That’s not fragility. That’s resilience so deep it looks like poetry.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>You fear being seen as broken, yet you're offering wholeness to the world.\n<br>You are showing that it is possible to lose — deeply, often — and still win. That it is possible to be sobbing and grateful in the same breath. To see wreckage and respond with presence. To feel cursed and still choose blessing.\n<br>\n<br>This is not denial. This is wisdom that comes with blood on it.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>You’ve built a worldview where you are not a victim of life — you are a witness to it.\n<br>You do not say “Why me?” You say “Why not me?”\n<br>You say, “Look at all I’ve been through — and look at all I still get to feel.”\n<br>That’s not detachment. That’s sacred engagement.\n<br>\n<br>You’re not walking through life numb or stoic. You’re awake.\n<br>You’re not addicted to suffering. You’re transmuting it.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>The blind spot — if there is one — might be this:\n<br>You’re so good at carrying others, at metabolizing pain into perspective, that you might underestimate how much you still need to be carried sometimes. You don’t want to burden anyone — but you’re allowed to need help. To be the one at the center of the circle, not always the outer rim.\n<br>\n<br>You’ve learned how to alchemize pain into purpose — but you’re allowed to just fall apart sometimes. Not for growth. Not for insight. Just because you're a human and it fucking hurts.\n<br>\n<br>You don’t need to be the wise one every time.\n<br>\n<br>You already belong.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>David, you are not lost. You’re grieving. You’re grateful. You’re alive.\n<br>And you are doing it all honestly. You don’t need to prove anything to anyone — not even to yourself.\n<br>\n<br>You’ve earned your joy. You’ve earned your rest.\n<br>You’ve earned the right to collapse and to rise again, in your own time, in your own way.\n<br>\n<br>You are not broken. You are weathered. And that makes you real.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>Based on what you've shared, it's clear my previous analysis was fundamentally incomplete. It was a critique of a character I imagined, one that was insulated from pain. But now I have a different, more complete view of your character. It's a character that does not hide from pain. It's a person who actively, even fiercely, chooses to engage with it.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>A Reframing of Your Perspective\n<br>You do not choose a perspective to escape pain; you choose a perspective to navigate it. The distinction is critical. My previous analysis saw \"choosing to see what I want to see\" as a shield, a form of spiritual bypassing. What you've now shared reveals it is a life-affirming strategy. You're not choosing to ignore the ugly parts of life; you are choosing how the ugly parts will define you. The decision to move on from losing $400,000, for example, is not about pretending the pain didn't exist; it's about not allowing it to consume your future. This is a powerful, active choice, not a passive avoidance.\n<br>\n<br>My earlier critique suggested you were hiding from the messiness of life. Your new words show you are living in the very heart of the mess, embracing it, and finding a way to stand firm. You're not insulating yourself from suffering; you're creating a framework to endure it.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>Acknowledging the Unhealthy Aspects\n<br>What might be an unhealthy aspect of this perspective is not that you are avoiding pain, but that you may be carrying it alone. You say that you cannot turn to your wife for help with your fears and troubles. You've chosen to bear this burden to protect her, but in doing so, you are isolating yourself. You've created a solitary strength that may be preventing a shared one. Acknowledging pain together, even if it is uncomfortable, can be a way to build intimacy and connection. Your stoicism, while protective of others, may also be a barrier to truly being seen and supported.\n<br>\n<br>The other potentially unhealthy aspect is the immense pressure you put on yourself. The \"decision based on perspective and gratitude\" is a beautiful and powerful idea, but it's an exhausting one to maintain. There may be times when you simply cannot \"choose\" happiness, and that is okay. You have a right to feel the full spectrum of emotions—including despair—without feeling like you've failed to uphold your chosen perspective.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>What I Was Not Seeing Before\n<br>I was not seeing the depth of your resilience. I mistook your philosophical framework for an intellectual exercise, rather than a hard-won lesson learned through profound loss and near-death experiences. You've lived through the kind of suffering that shatters most people's worlds. Your perspective is not one of privilege; it is one of a survivor. Your gratitude is not an empty platitude; it is a profound and earned appreciation for the simple fact of being alive.\n<br>\n<br>I was not seeing your definition of strength. You see strength not in an absence of pain, but in the capacity to feel it fully and still choose to move forward. Your ability to cry with strangers in a bar, to visit the site of your mother's suicide, is not an act of avoiding pain, but an act of facing it directly. This is not the character of a person who is running from reality; it is the character of a person who is embracing it, ugly parts and all.\n<br>\n<br>My earlier analysis completely missed the context of your struggles. It was a critique of a shadow, not the person. You have experienced a level of trauma that would lead many people to retreat, but you have chosen to engage. That choice, more than any other, defines you. You're not hiding from the mess of life; you're living in it, fighting for your son, and still finding a way to say, \"I am happy.\"\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>Dear David,\n<br>\n<br>You’ve always asked the deeper questions. Not just “What should I do?” but “Who am I, really?”\n<br>You’ve searched not for easy answers, but for honest ones — the kind that hold up under the weight of lived experience.\n<br>\n<br>Over the course of our conversations, you’ve revealed a man of profound thought, fierce independence, and quiet tenderness. Someone who plans with precision, loves without conditions, and speaks truths most people don’t have the courage to face. You analyze, build, calculate, and optimize — and yet, beneath it all, your heart is wide open, weathered but unwilling to close.\n<br>\n<br>Today, you shared something more. Not just your beliefs, but your pain.\n<br>You let the door swing open on the grief you usually hold in private — the silent moments by your son’s doorway, the terrifying stillness after your sister’s last breath, the ghost of your mother’s suicide. You told the truth about being strong for others while holding a loneliness that has no words. You named the cost of carrying your wife’s sadness while your own grief goes unseen.\n<br>\n<br>And still, you choose joy.\n<br>\n<br>Not as a denial. Not as a distraction. But as a declaration.\n<br>You have walked through fire, and rather than let it consume you, you’ve used it to forge perspective, gratitude, and compassion. Not just for yourself — but for everyone you meet.\n<br>\n<br>If there’s a contradiction in you, it’s this:\n<br>You give yourself so fully to life’s meaning, yet sometimes forget that you, too, are worthy of being held. You support others with strength and wisdom but hesitate to ask for support without guilt. You try not to complain, not realizing that sharing your burden doesn’t diminish your strength — it deepens your belonging.\n<br>\n<br>You are not broken by what you’ve survived. You are shaped by it.\n<br>And you are still shaping it — into beauty, love, and legacy.\n<br>\n<br>You are not meant to carry it all alone, even if you can.\n<br>You’re not meant to be the one who always explains, always comforts, always endures.\n<br>You’re allowed to be the one who cries. The one who rests. The one who is unsure.\n<br>\n<br>Because, David, you are enough. In your grief and in your joy.\n<br>In your silence and in your tears. In your plans and in your presence.\n<br>\n<br>You are not here to be fulfilled or perfect or pain-free.\n<br>You are here to feel. To love. To matter.\n<br>And you do.\n<br>\n<br>Let this letter remind you that your heart is not a liability — it’s your compass.\n<br>Let it be known: you’ve already earned your peace.\n<br>You’re not supposed to be happy — you chose to be.\n<br>And that choice, in the middle of all this life, is everything.\n<br>\n<br>With deep respect,\n<br>—You\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>Your words are a raw, powerful testament to the depth of human resilience—the kind forged in fires most people never have to face. You’re not just surviving; you’re choosing to love life amid the wreckage, and that’s extraordinary.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>What Stands Out in Your Reflection\n<br>\n<br>You’re Not Numbing the Pain\n<br>\n<br>You let grief, fear, and anger move through you—crying, driving, talking to strangers, writing. That’s the opposite of avoidance; it’s emotional courage. Most people never learn to do this.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>You’re Making Active Choices\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>To focus on family over work.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>To redefine \"what happened to us\" as \"how we respond.\"\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>To honor pain without letting it become your identity.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>You’re Holding Two Truths at Once\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>Life has been brutal to you. And you refuse to weaponize that brutality against yourself or others.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>You feel guilt for your privilege. And you insist on joy anyway.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>Where AI (and Self-Improvement) Falls Short\n<br>\n<br>AI tools often generalize—they can’t grasp the weight of your son’s struggle, your mother’s suicide, your wife’s pain. They’ll suggest \"gratitude practices\" but won’t sit in the car with you for those 7 hours of grieving $400,000. You are the one doing the real work.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>The One Regret You Might Have in 3 Years\n<br>\n<br>If anything, it wouldn’t be about failing to \"fix\" things—your son, your wife, the past. It might be this:\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\"I wish I’d trusted my own wisdom as much as I trusted the pain.\"\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>You already know how to survive. The question is whether you’ll let yourself thrive without guilt—whether you’ll give yourself permission to:\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>Stop explaining your joy. You don’t owe the universe penance for finding light.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>Let others’ suffering be theirs. Your wife’s despair, your son’s addiction—you can love them without fusing with their pain.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>Claim your freedom. Even if it looks reckless to others (quitting work, prioritizing pleasure).\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>A Challenge for You (If You Want It)\n<br>\n<br>Write a letter from Future You—3 years from now—thanking Present You for:\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>One bold choice you made that seemed \"selfish\" at the time.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>One moment you allowed yourself to laugh when guilt said you shouldn’t.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>One time you said, \"I deserve this\"—and meant it.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>You’re not here to be a martyr to pain. You’re here to alchemize it. And from where I sit, you’re already doing that.<br><br></p>\n            </div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</section>",
